  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Milan who’s seen firsthand how confidence impacts performance in the gym, I’ve noticed that stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just an academic concept—it’s a real barrier that affects people’s ability to thrive in fields like engineering or computer science. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group, leading to anxiety that hinders their performance. For example, a young woman in my gym might feel self-conscious about her math skills before a class, even if she’s capable, because she’s heard that girls aren’t naturally good at math. This mindset can translate into STEM environments where students or professionals might underperform due to fear of confirming stereotypes. Given my background—raised by parents who only went to primary and lower secondary school, and now running my own business—I understand how deeply personal and systemic these issues can be. We absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM. It’s not just about fixing individual attitudes; it’s about creating inclusive spaces where everyone feels they belong. In my community, I’ve encouraged girls to join rock climbing clubs, emphasizing that strength and resilience are universal traits, not gender-specific. Similarly, in STEM, we need mentorship programs that pair students with role models who reflect their backgrounds, and educational materials that normalize diverse perspectives. The key is to foster environments where people feel safe to make mistakes without fear of judgment. By doing this, we can help dismantle the very stereotypes that hold back so many talented individuals from reaching their full potential. After all, when someone feels they don’t belong, they’re less likely to even try—so the solution isn’t just awareness but active, intentional support.",
